1164":"1164","about 1164":"circa 1164","Skipwith Selby,Yorkshire,England.":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1164–":"about 1164–Deceased","1178–Female":"1178–Deceased","1164–Male":"1164–Deceased","1178":"1178","1164":"1164","about 1164":"about 1164","Skipwith Selby,Yorkshire,England.":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Skipworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): habitational name from Skipwith (East Yorkshire), from Old Northumbrian <i>scīp</i> (Old English <i>scēap</i> ‘sheep’), + Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farm’, later replaced by Old Norse <i>vithr</i> ‘wood’; initial <i>Sk-</i>, instead of <i>Sh-</i>, is also due to Scandinavian influence."],"variants":[{"name":"Skipwith","meanings":["English (Surrey): variant of   Skipworth  .","History: The main Skipwith family held the manor of Skipwith in England in the early Middle Ages, and direct descendants can be traced to the present day. In the 13th century they moved from Yorkshire to Lincolnshire, where their principal seat was at southern Ormsby. In the early 17th century there was further migration, to Leicestershire, Warwickshire, and across the Atlantic to VA. Other bearers of the name seem to have been tenants of Lincolnshire manors held by the Skipworth family, and to have taken the surname of their overlords."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Skipworth was born about 1164, in Skipwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1164–":"umbes 1164–Surnud","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1178":"1178","1164":"1164","about 1164":"umbes 1164","Skipwith Selby,Yorkshire,England.":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1164–":"noin 1164–Kuollut","1178–Female":"1178–Kuollut","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1178":"1178","1164":"1164","about 1164":"noin 1164","Skipwith Selby,Yorkshire,England.":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1164–":"environ 1164–Décédé","1178–Female":"1178–Décédée","1164–Male":"1164–Décédé","1178":"1178","1164":"1164","about 1164":"environ 1164","Skipwith Selby,Yorkshire,England.":"Skipwith, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir William Skipworth est né environ 1164, à Skipwith, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1164–":"um 1164–Verstorben","1178–Female":"1178–Verstorben","1164–Male":"1164–Verstorben","1178":"1178","1164":"1164","about 1164":"um 1164","Skipwith Selby,Yorkshire,England.":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Sir William Skipworth wurde um 1164 in Skipwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"about 1164–":"about 1164–Desede","1178–Female":"1178–Desede","1164–Male":"1164–Desede","1178":"1178","1164":"1164","about 1164":"about 1164","Skipwith Selby,Yorkshire,England.":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"about 1164–":"1164 körül–elhunyt","1178–Female":"1178–elhunyt","1164–Male":"1164–elhunyt","1178":"1178","1164":"1164","about 1164":"1164 körül","Skip